staff availability","Staff seniority and years of experience","Task complexity and required competencies","Equal distribution of workload","Personal relationships with team members"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach involves assessing \u003Cstrong\u003Etask complexity and required competencies\u003C/strong\u003E. This includes evaluating:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe nature and complexity of the task\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe skills and qualifications required\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe recipient\u0027s scope of practice and competency level\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EClear communication of specific instructions and timeframes\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EConfirmation of understanding and plan for supervision\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgency of tasks and staff availability\u003C/strong\u003E - While important considerations, these factors alone do not ensure safe and appropriate delegation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaff seniority and years of experience\u003C/strong\u003E - Experience alone does not guarantee competency for specific tasks\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual distribution of workload\u003C/strong\u003E - This approach ignores individual capabilities and scope of practice requirements\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersonal relationships with team members\u003C/strong\u003E - Professional decisions about delegation should be based on competency, not personal factors\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EEffective delegation requires careful assessment of both the task requirements and the delegate\u0027s capabilities, followed by clear communication and appropriate supervision to ensure patient 